Here is the basic structure of a Flappy Bird game using HTML. You'll need JavaScript for the game logic and this is a very basic implementation and may not have the features that a real Flappy Bird game would have. 

HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
    <div id="bird"></div>
    <div id="pipes"></div>
    <button onclick="startGame()">Start Game</button>
</body>
</html>
```

CSS:
```css
#bird {
    position: absolute;
    width: 50px;
    height: 50px;
    background-color: blue;
}

#pipes {
    position: absolute;
    width: 50px;
    height: 100px;
    background-color: green;
}
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
function startGame() {
    let bird = document.getElementById('bird');
    let pipes = Array.from(document.getElementById('pipes'));
    let gameTime = 0;

    // Move bird up when spacebar pressed
    document.addEventListener('keydown', function(e) {
        if(e.key === ' ') {
            bird.style.top = parseInt(bird.style.top, 10) - 50 + 'px';
        }
    });

    setInterval(function() {
        // Move pipes from right to left
        for(let i = 0; i < pipes.length; i++) {
            pipes[i].style.left = parseInt(pipes[i].style.left, 10) - 5 + 'px';
        }

        gameTime++;

        // If bird hits a pipe, end game
        for(let i = 0; i < pipes.length; i++) {
            if(parseInt(bird.style.top, 10) === parseInt(pipes[i].style.top, 10)) {
                alert('Game Over');
            }
        }
    }, 10);
}
```

Note: This code does not handle collision between the pipes and the top or bottom of the screen and does not add new pipes at regular intervals. For a full-featured Flappy Bird game, you would need to add these features and more. You could use a game framework, such as Phaser.js, which could provide these features and more for free. They also have a community created Flappy Bird tutorial that uses Phaser.js.

